<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-289-062  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 289 062.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  March 26 1990 v7 n13 p4(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Telecommuting may help firms keep good workers; high turnoverforcing companies to offer options.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Panepinto, Joe.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>As the work force becomes smaller and more diverse, companies arestarting to offer telecommuting as an option for the two growingsegments of the workforce: retired workers and working mothers.andO;Telecommuting and flexible work-at-home schedules are expected tohelp companies retain desirable employees.andP;  A 1989 survey showedthat more than one million American workers telecommute.andP;  Lessthan nine percent of the number work for companies with 1,000 ormore employees.andP;  A survey of Fortune 1,000 companies also showsthat only four percent have telecommuting programs in place,although another 13 percent are piloting or are planning toimplement a program in 1991.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Employee RelationsWork at HomeTelecommutingManagement.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>